# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: actinomycetota
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] The Acanthocephala were long thought to be a discrete phylum.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Recent genome analysis has shown that they are descended from, and should be considered as, highly modified rotifers.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] This unified taxon is sometimes known as Syndermata, or simply as Rotifera, with the acanthocephalans described as a subclass of a rotifer class Hemirotatoria.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] The earliest recognisable description of Acanthocephala – a worm with a proboscis armed with hooks – was made by Italian author Francesco Redi (1684).
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] In 1771, Joseph Koelreuter proposed the name Acanthocephala.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Philipp Ludwig Statius Müller independently called them *Echinorhynchus* in 1776.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Karl Rudolphi in 1809 formally named them Acanthocephala.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] The oldest known member of the group is the Middle Jurassic (living approximately 165 million years ago) taxon *Juracanthocephalus daohugouensis* known from the Jiulongshan Formation (China).
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] The fossil record of the group also includes eggs found in a coprolite from the Late Cretaceous Bauru Group of Brazil, around 70–80 million years old, likely from a crocodyliform.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] The group may have originated substantially earlier.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans are highly adapted to a parasitic mode of life, and have lost many organs and structures through evolutionary processes.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] This makes determining relationships with other higher taxa through morphological comparison problematic.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] A 2016 phylogenetic analysis of the gene order in the mitochondria suggests that Seisonidea and Acanthocephala are sister clades and that the Eurotatoria are the sister clade to this group, producing the cladogram below.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Several morphological characteristics distinguish acanthocephalans from other phyla of parasitic worms.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans lack a mouth or alimentary canal.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] This is a feature they share with the cestoda (tapeworms), although the two groups are not closely related.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Adult stages live in the intestines of their host and uptake nutrients which have been digested by the host, directly, through their body surface.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] The acanthocephalans lack an excretory system, although some species have been shown to possess flame cells (protonephridia).
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] The most notable feature of the acanthocephala is the presence of an anterior, protrudable proboscis that is usually covered with spiny hooks (hence the common name: thorny or spiny headed worm).
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] The proboscis bears rings of recurved hooks arranged in horizontal rows, and it is by means of these hooks that the animal attaches itself to the tissues of its host.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] The hooks may be of two or three shapes, usually: longer, more slender hooks are arranged along the length of the proboscis, with several rows of more sturdy, shorter nasal hooks around the base of the proboscis.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] The proboscis is used to pierce the gut wall of the final host, and hold the parasite fast while it completes its life cycle.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Like the body, the proboscis is hollow, and its cavity is separated from the body cavity by a *septum* or *proboscis sheath*.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Traversing the cavity of the proboscis are muscle-strands inserted into the tip of the proboscis at one end and into the septum at the other.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Their contraction causes the proboscis to be invaginated into its cavity.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] The whole proboscis apparatus can also be, at least partially, withdrawn into the body cavity, and this is effected by two retractor muscles which run from the posterior aspect of the septum to the body wall.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Some of the acanthocephalans (perforating acanthocephalans) can insert their proboscis in the intestine of the host and open the way to the abdominal cavity.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] The size of these animals varies greatly, ranging from a few millimetres in length to *Macracanthorhynchus hirudinaceus*, which measures from 10 to 65 centimetres (3.9 to 25.6 in).
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] A curious feature shared by both larva and adult is the large size of many of the cells, e.g. the nerve cells and cells forming the uterine bell.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Polyploidy is common, with up to 343n having been recorded in some species.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] The body surface of the acanthocephala is peculiar.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Externally, the skin has a thin tegument that covers the epidermis and consists of a syncytium with no cell walls.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] The syncytium is traversed by a series of branching tubules containing fluid and is controlled by a few wandering, amoeboid nuclei.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Inside the syncytium is an irregular layer of circular muscle fibres, and within this again some rather scattered longitudinal fibres; there is no endothelium.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] In their micro-structure the muscular fibres resemble those of nematodes.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Except for the absence of the longitudinal fibres the skin of the proboscis resembles that of the body, but the fluid-containing tubules of the proboscis are shut off from those of the body.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] The canals of the proboscis open into a circular vessel which runs round its base.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] From the circular canal two sac-like projections called the *lemnisci* run into the cavity of the body, alongside the proboscis cavity.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Each consists of a prolongation of the syncytial material of the proboscis skin, penetrated by canals and sheathed with a muscular coat.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] They seem to act as reservoirs into which the fluid which is used to keep the proboscis "erect" can withdraw when it is retracted, and from which the fluid can be driven out when it is wished to expand the proboscis.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] The central ganglion of the nervous system lies behind the proboscis sheath or septum.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] It innervates the proboscis and projects two stout trunks posteriorly which supply the body.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Each of these trunks is surrounded by muscles, and this nerve-muscle complex is called a *retinaculum*.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] In the male at least there is also a genital ganglion.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Some scattered papillae may possibly be sense-organs.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalans have complex life cycles, involving a number of hosts, for both developmental and resting stages.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Complete life cycles have been worked out for only 25 species.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] The Acanthocephala are dioecious (an individual organism is either male or female).
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] There is a structure called the *genital ligament* which runs from the posterior end of the proboscis sheath to the posterior end of the body.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] In the male, two testes lie on either side of this.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Each opens in a vas deferens which bears three diverticula or *vesiculae seminales*.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] The male also possesses three pairs of cement glands, found behind the testes, which pour their secretions through a duct into the vasa deferentia.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] These unite and end in a penis which opens posteriorly.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] In the female, the ovaries are found, like the testes, as rounded bodies along the ligament.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] From the ovaries, masses of ova dehisce into the body cavity, floating in its fluids for fertilization by male's sperm.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] After fertilization, each egg contains a developing embryo.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] (These embryos hatch into first stage larva.) The fertilized eggs are brought into the uterus by actions of the *uterine bell*, a funnel like opening continuous with the uterus.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] At the junction of the bell and the uterus there is a second, smaller opening situated dorsally.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] The bell "swallows" the matured eggs and passes them on into the uterus.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] (Immature embryos are passed back into the body cavity through the dorsal opening.) From the uterus, mature eggs leave the female's body via her oviduct, pass into the host's alimentary canal and are expelled from the host's body within feces.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Having been expelled by the female, the acanthocephalan egg is released along with the feces of the host.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] For development to occur, the egg, containing the acanthor, needs to be ingested by an arthropod, usually a crustacean (there is one known life cycle which uses a mollusc as a first intermediate host).
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Inside the intermediate host, the acanthor is released from the egg and develops into an acanthella.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] It then penetrates the gut wall, moves into the body cavity, encysts, and begins transformation into the infective cystacanth stage.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] This form has all the organs of the adult save the reproductive ones.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] The parasite is released when the first intermediate host is ingested.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] This can be by a suitable final host, in which case the cystacanth develops into a mature adult, or by a paratenic host, in which the parasite again forms a cyst.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] When consumed by a suitable final host, the cycstacant *excysts*, everts its proboscis and pierces the gut wall.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] It then feeds, grows and develops its sexual organs.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] The male uses the excretions of its *cement glands* to plug the vagina of the female, preventing subsequent matings from occurring.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Embryos develop inside the female, and the life cycle repeats.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Thorny-headed worms begin their life cycle inside invertebrates that reside in marine or freshwater systems.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] One example is *Polymorphus paradoxus.* *Gammarus lacustris*, a small crustacean that inhabits ponds and rivers, is one invertebrate that *P. paradoxus* may occupy; ducks are one of the definitive hosts.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] This crustacean is preyed on by ducks and hides by avoiding light and staying away from the surface.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] However, infection by *P. paradoxus* changes its behavior and appearance in a number of ways that increase its chance of being eaten.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] First, infection significantly reduces *G. lacustris'*s photophobia; as a result, it becomes attracted toward light and swims to the surface.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Second, an infected organism will even go so far as to find a rock or a plant on the surface, clamp its mouth down, and latch on, making it easy prey for the duck.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Finally, infection reduces the pigment distribution and amount in *G. lacustris,* causing the host to turn blue; unlike their normal brown colour, this makes the crustacean stand out and increases the chance the duck will see it.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Experiments have shown that altered serotonin levels are likely responsible for at least some of these changes in behaviour.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] One experiment found that serotonin induces clinging behavior in *G. lacustris* similar to that seen in infected organisms.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Another showed that infected *G. lacustris* had approximately 3 times as many serotonin-producing sites in its ventral nerve cord.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Acanthocephalosis, a disease caused by *Acanthacephalus* infection, is prevalent in aquaculture, occurring in Atlantic salmon, rainbow and brown trout, tilapia, and tambaqui.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Increasing occurrence in Brazilian farming of tambaqui has been reported, and in 2003 *Acanthacephalus* was first reported in cultured red snapper in Taiwan.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] The life cycle of *Polymorphus* spp. normally occurs between sea ducks (e.g. eiders and scoters) and small crabs.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Infections found in commercial-sized lobsters in Canada were probably acquired from crabs that form an important dietary item of lobsters.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Cystacanths occurring in lobsters can cause economic loss to fishermen.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] There are no known methods of prevention or control.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Although they rarely infect humans, worms in the phylum Acanthocephala cause the disease acanthocephaliasis in humans.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] The earliest known infection was found in a prehistoric man in Utah.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] This infection was dated to 1869 ± 160 BC.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] The species involved was thought to be *Moniliformis clarki* which is still common in the area.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] The first report of an isolate in historic times was by Lambl in 1859 when he isolated *Macracanthorhynchus hirudinaceus* from a child in Prague.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Lindemann in 1865 reported that this organism was commonly isolated in Russia.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] The reason for this was discovered by Schneider in 1871 when he found that an intermediate host, the scarabaeid beetle grub, was commonly eaten raw.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] The first report of clinical symptoms was by Calandruccio who in 1888 while in Italy infected himself by ingesting larvae.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] He reported gastrointestinal disturbances and shed eggs in two weeks.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Subsequent natural infections have since been reported.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Eight species have been isolated from humans to date.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] *Moniliformis moniliformis* is the most common isolate.
[src:actinomycetota/acanthocephala] Other isolates include *Acanthocephalus bufonis* and *Corynosoma strumosum*.
[src:actinomycetota/acidimicrobiia] The ***Acidimicrobiia*** are a class of Actinomycetota, in which three families, eight genera, and nine species have been described, *Acidimicrobium ferrooxidans* is the type species of the order.
[src:actinomycetota/acidimicrobiia] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature (LPSN) and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriia] The "**Acidobacteriia**" is a class of Acidobacteriota.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriia] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriia] Numbered orders do not yet have any cultured representatives.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] Members of this phylum are physiologically diverse, and can be found in a variety of environments including soil, decomposing wood, hot springs, oceans, caves, and metal-contaminated soils.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] The members of this phylum are particularly abundant in soil habitats representing up to 52% of the total bacterial community.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] Environmental factors such as pH and nutrients have been seen to drive Acidobacteriota dynamics.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] Many Acidobacteriota are acidophilic, including the first described member of the phylum, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] There is much that is unknown about Acidobacteria both in their form and function.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] Thus, this is a growing field of microbiology.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] Some of this uncertainty can be attributed to the difficulty with which these bacteria are grown in the laboratory.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] There has been recent success in propagation by using low concentrations of nutrients in combination with high amounts of CO2, yet, progress is still quite slow.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] These new methods have only allowed approximately 30% of subdivisions to have species documented.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] Additionally, many of the samples sequenced do not have taxonomic names as they have not yet been fully characterized.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] This area of study is a very current topic, and scientific understanding is expected to grow and change as new information comes to light.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] Other notable species are *Holophaga foetida*, *Geothrix fermentans*, *Acanthopleuribacter pedis* and *Bryobacter aggregatus*.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] Since they have only recently been discovered and the large majority have not been cultured, the ecology and metabolism of these bacteria is not well understood.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] However, these bacteria may be an important contributor to ecosystems, since they are particularly abundant within soils.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivisions 1, 4, and 6 are found to be particularly abundant in soils.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] As well as their natural soil habitat, unclassified subdivision 2 Acidobacteriota have also been identified as a contaminant of DNA extraction kit reagents, which may lead to their erroneous appearance in microbiota or metagenomic datasets.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 have been found to dominate in low pH conditions.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] Additionally, Acidobacteriota from acid mine drainage have been found to be more adapted to acidic pH conditions (pH 2–3) compared to Acidobacteriota from soils, potentially due to cell specialization and enzyme stability.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] The G+C content of Acidobacteria genomes are consistent within their subdivisions - above 60% for group V fragments and roughly 10% lower for group III fragments.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] The majority of Acidobacteriota are considered aerobes.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] There are some Acidobacteriota that are considered anaerobes within subdivision 8 and subdivision 23.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] It has been found that some strains of Acidobacteriota originating from soils have the genomic potential to respire oxygen at atmospheric and sub-atmospheric concentrations.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] Members of the *Acidobacteriota* phylum have been considered oligotrophic bacteria due to high abundances in low organic carbon environments.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] However, the variation in this phylum may indicate that they may not have the same ecological strategy.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] The first species, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*, of this phylum was discovered in 1991.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] However, Acidobacteriota were not recognized as a distinct clade until 1997, and were not recognized as a phylum until 2012.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] In an effort to further classify Acidobacteria, 16S rRNA gene regions were sequenced from many different strains.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] These sequences lead to the formation of subdivisions within the phyla.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] Today, there are 26 accepted subdivisions recognized in the Ribosomal Database Project.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] Much of this variety comes from populations of acidobacteria found in soils contaminated with uranium.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] Therefore, most of the known species in this phyla are concentrated in a few of the subdivisions, the largest being #1.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] Most of these microbes are aerobes, and they are all heterotrophic.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] Subdivision 1 contains 11 of the known genera in addition to the majority of the species that have been able to be cultivated thus far.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] Within the 22 known genera, there are 40 conclusive species.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] The genera are divided amongst subdivisions 3, 4, 8, 10, 23, and 1.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] As the Acidobateria are a developing area of microbiology, it is hypothesized that these numbers will change drastically with further study.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] Some members of subdivision 1 are able to use D-glucose, D-xylose, and lactose as carbon sources, but are unable to use fucose or sorbose.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 also contain enzymes such as galactosidases used in the breakdown of sugars.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 4 have been found to use chitin as a carbon source.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] Despite the presence of genetic information generally known to encode for carbohydrate processing machinery in various genera of Acidobacteria, several experimental studies have demonstrated the inability to break down various polysaccharides.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] Cellulose is the main component of plant cell walls and a seemingly opportune resource for carbon.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] However, only a single species across all subdivisions has been shown to process it, *Telmactobacter bradus* from subvision 1.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] Researchers believe that an additional factor in the lack of understanding of carbon degradation by acidobacteria may stem from the present limited ability to provide adequate cultivation conditions.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] To study the natural behavior of these bacteria, they must grow and live in a controlled, observable environment.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] If such a habitat cannot be provided, recorded data cannot reliably report on the activity of the microbes in question.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] Therefore, the inconsistencies between genome sequence based predictions and observed carbon processes may be explained by present study methods.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] There has been no clear evidence that Acidobacteriota are involved in nitrogen-cycle processes such as nitrification, denitrification, or nitrogen fixation.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] However, *Geothrix fermantans* was shown to be able to reduce nitrate and contained the norB gene.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] The NorB gene was also identified in *Koribacter verstailis* and *Solibacter usitatus*.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] In addition, the presence of the nirA gene has been observed in members of subdivision 1.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] Additionally, to date, all genomes have been described to directly uptake ammonium via ammonium channel transporter family genes.
[src:actinomycetota/acidobacteriota] Acidobacteriota can use both inorganic and organic nitrogen as their nitrogen sources.
[src:actinomycetota/acidulidesulfobacteriota] Acidulidesulfobacteriota are ecologically significant in biogeochemical cycling, especially with respect to sulfur and iron.
[src:actinomycetota/acidulidesulfobacteriota] Their genomes show evidence of interaction with viruses, which can influence host metabolic functions including folate biosynthesis and sulfur pathways.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomyces] Like various other anaerobes, *Actinomyces* species are fastidious, thus not easy to culture and isolate.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomyces] Clinical laboratories do culture and isolate them, but a negative result does not rule out infection, because it may be due simply to reluctance to grow *in vitro*.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomyces] Phylogenetic trees based on 16S ribosomal RNA (16SrRNA) sequences have shown that the genus *Actinomyces* is quite diverse, exhibiting polyphyletic branching into several clusters.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomyces] The genera *Actinomyces* and *Mobiluncus* form a monophyletic clade in a phylogenetic tree constructed using RpoB, RpoC, and DNA gyrase B protein sequences.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomyces] This clade is also strongly supported by a conserved signature indel consisting of a three-amino-acid insertion in isoleucine tRNA synthetase found only in the species of the genera *Actinomyces* and *Mobiluncus*.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomyces] Actinomycota are normally present in the gingiva, and are the most common cause of infection in dental procedures and oral abscesses.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomyces] Many *Actinomyces* species are opportunistic pathogens of humans and other mammals, particularly in the oral cavity.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomyces] In rare cases, these bacteria can cause actinomycosis, a disease characterized by the formation of abscesses in the mouth, lungs, or the gastrointestinal tract.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomyces] Actinomycosis is most frequently caused by *A. israelii*, which may also cause endocarditis, though the resulting symptoms may be similar to those resulting from infections by other bacterial species.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomyces] The genus is typically the cause of oral-cervicofacial disease.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomyces] It is characterized by a painless "lumpy jaw".
[src:actinomycetota/actinomyces] Lymphadenopathy is uncommon in this form of the disease.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomyces] Another form of actinomycosis is thoracic disease, which is often misdiagnosed as a neoplasm, as it forms a mass that extends to the chest wall.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomyces] It arises from aspiration of organisms from the oropharynx.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomyces] Symptoms include chest pain, fever, and weight loss.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomyces] Abdominal disease is another manifestation of actinomycosis.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomyces] This can lead to a sinus tract that drains to the abdominal wall or the perianal area.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomyces] Symptoms include fever, abdominal pain, and weight loss.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomyces] Pelvic actinomycosis is a rare but proven complication of use of intrauterine devices.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomyces] In extreme cases, pelvic abscesses might develop.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomyces] Treatment of pelvic actinomycosis associated with intrauterine devices involves removal of the device and antibiotic treatment.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomyces] Actinomycosis may be considered when a patient has chronic progression of disease across tissue planes that is mass-like at times, sinus tract development that may heal and recur, and refractory infection after a typical course of antibiotics.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomyces] Treatment for actinomycosis consists of antibiotics such as penicillin or amoxicillin for 5 to 12 months, as well as surgery if the disease is extensive.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomycetota] The **Actinomycetota** (previously known as **"Actinobacteria"**) are a diverse phylum of Gram-positive bacteria with high guanine-cytosine content (GC content or G+C content).
[src:actinomycetota/actinomycetota] They are of great importance to land flora because of their contributions to soil systems.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomycetota] In soil, they help decompose organic matter of dead organisms so the molecules can be taken up anew by plants.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomycetota] While this role is also played by fungi, actinomycetota are much smaller and likely do not occupy the same ecological niche.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomycetota] In this role, the colonies often grow extensive mycelia, as fungi do, and the name of an important order of the phylum, Actinomycetales (the actinomycetes), reflects that they were long believed to be fungi.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomycetota] Some soil actinomycetota (such as *Frankia*) live symbiotically with the plants whose roots pervade the soil, fixing nitrogen for the plants in exchange for access to some of the plant's saccharides.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomycetota] Other species, such as many members of the genus *Mycobacterium*, are important pathogens.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomycetota] Beyond the great interest in Actinomycetota for their soil role, much is yet to be learned about them.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomycetota] Although currently understood primarily as soil bacteria, they might be more abundant in fresh waters.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota is one of the dominant bacterial phyla and contains one of the largest of bacterial genera: *Streptomyces*.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomycetota] *Streptomyces* and other actinomycetota are major contributors to biological buffering of soils.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomycetota] They are also the source of many antibiotics.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomycetota] Bacteria of the Actinomycetota genus *Bifidobacterium* are the most common in the microbiome of human infants.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomycetota] Although adults have fewer bifidobacteria, intestinal bifidobacteria help maintain the mucosal barrier and reduce lipopolysaccharides in the intestine.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomycetota] Although some of the largest and most complex bacterial cells belong to the Actinomycetota, the group of marine Actinomarinales has been described as possessing the smallest free-living prokaryotic cells.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomycetota] Some Siberian or Antarctic biofilms of these bacteria are said to have the longest lifespan of any organism on Earth, frozen in permafrost at around half a million years ago.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomycetota] Most actinomycetota of medical or economic significance are in class Actinomycetia, and belong to the order Actinomycetales.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomycetota] While many of these cause disease in humans, *Streptomyces* is notable as a source of antibiotics.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomycetota] Of those actinomycetota not in the Actinomycetales, *Gardnerella* is one of the most researched.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomycetota] Classification of *Gardnerella* is controversial, and MeSH catalogues it as both a Gram-positive and Gram-negative organism.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota-derived antibiotics that are important in medicine include aminoglycosides, anthracyclines, chloramphenicol, macrolides, tetracyclines, etc.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomycetota] Actinomycetota have high guanine and cytosine content in their DNA.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomycetota] The GC content of actinomycetota can be as high as 70%, though some may have a low GC content.
[src:actinomycetota/actinomycetota] Analysis of glutamine synthetase sequence has been suggested for phylogenetic analysis of the Actinomycetota.
